{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 02:59:47.606394", "event": "llm_end", "text": "It looks like you’re trying to find the IP address of a device that’s connected to your network (via your router).  \nBelow are a few common ways to discover that address from a computer that’s already on the same network.  \nPick the method that matches your operating system and the type of device you’re looking for.\n\n---\n\n## 1.  From the computer that’s already on the network\n\n### Windows\n\n1. **Open a command prompt**  \n   Press `Win + R`, type `cmd`, and hit **Enter**.\n\n2. **Run `ipconfig`**  \n   ```cmd\n   ipconfig\n   ```\n   Look for the *IPv4 Address* under the active network adapter (e.g., “Ethernet” or “Wi‑Fi”).  \n   That’s the computer’s own IP address.\n\n3. **Find other devices**  \n   - **View the router’s client list**  \n     Open a web browser and go to your router’s admin page (often `192.168.1.1`, `192.168.0.1`, or `10.0.0.1`).  \n     Log in with your admin credentials and look for a “Connected Devices,” “DHCP Clients,” or similar section.  \n     It will list each device’s hostname and IP address.\n\n   - **Use `arp -a`**  \n     ```cmd\n     arp -a\n     ```\n     This shows the ARP table: IP addresses mapped to MAC addresses that your computer has recently communicated with.  \n     If you know the MAC address of the target device, you can find its IP here.\n\n### macOS / Linux\n\n1. **Open a terminal**.\n\n2. **Run `ifconfig` or `ip a`**  \n   ```bash\n   ifconfig\n   # or\n   ip a\n   ```\n   Look for the `inet` address under the active interface (e.g., `en0`, `eth0`).  \n   That’s your computer’s IP.\n\n3. **Find other devices**  \n   - **Router’s client list** – same as above: log into the router’s web UI and look for a “Connected Devices” page.  \n   - **`arp -a`** – same as Windows:  \n     ```bash\n     arp -a\n     ```\n     Shows IP ↔ MAC mappings.\n\n---\n\n## 2.  From the router itself\n\nIf you have physical access to the router:\n\n1. **Log into the router’s admin interface**  \n   Open a browser and navigate to the router’s default gateway (you can find it with `ipconfig` → *Default Gateway* on Windows or `netstat -rn` → *default* on macOS/Linux).  \n   Log in with the admin username/password.\n\n2. **Navigate to the DHCP client list**  \n   Look for a section called “Attached Devices,” “LAN Status,” “DHCP Clients,” or similar.  \n   It will list every device that has obtained an IP address from the router, along with hostnames and MAC addresses.\n\n---\n\n## 3.  Using a network‑scanning tool\n\nIf you want a quick visual list of all devices on the network:\n\n- **Advanced IP Scanner** (Windows)  \n  Download and run it; it will scan the subnet and display all active IPs and hostnames.\n\n- **Angry IP Scanner** (cross‑platform)  \n  Similar to Advanced IP Scanner but works on Windows, macOS, and Linux.\n\n- **Nmap** (command line, cross‑platform)  \n  ```bash\n  nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24\n  ```\n  Replace `192.168.1.0/24` with your subnet.  \n  It will ping each address and list the ones that respond.\n\n---\n\n### Quick checklist\n\n| Step | What to do | Why it works |\n|------|------------|--------------|\n| 1 | Find your own IP (`ipconfig` / `ifconfig` / `ip a`) | Confirms you’re on the network. |\n| 2 | Log into the router’s web UI | Router knows every device that’s connected. |\n| 3 | Look for “Connected Devices” / “DHCP Clients” | Shows IP, hostname, MAC of each device. |\n| 4 | (Optional) Run `arp -a` | Shows recent IP↔MAC mappings if you can’t access the router. |\n| 5 | (Optional) Use a scanner | Gives a quick visual list if you prefer a GUI. |\n\n---\n\n**Tip:**  \nIf you’re trying to find a specific device (e.g., a printer, a Raspberry Pi, or a smart TV), look for its hostname or MAC address in the router’s client list. Many routers also allow you to rename devices for easier identification.\n\nLet me know if you need help with a specific router model or operating system, and I can give you more detailed instructions!", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-12T02:59:46.856887412Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 213677029231, "load_duration": 74390764, "prompt_eval_count": 8192, "prompt_eval_duration": 6894631441, "eval_count": 21539, "eval_duration": 206688203383, "model_name": "gpt-oss:20b"}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8192, "output_tokens": 21539, "total_tokens": 29731}}
